00:06:09.630 --> 00:06:13.410
I've always remembered that.

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:17.880 position:56%
Four years after this time, I was at
a convention in San Jose, California

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:21.870
and I had seen a woman
named Diana Birch,

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:26.190
who I had never personally met, but
we had corresponded over the years

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.440 position:56%
and I went up and introduced myself.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:35.160 position:56%
Well, as my name left my lips she
shouted, "Oh, you're the polar man."

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:38.980
And this is the kind of response
I often receive from people.

00:06:38.980 --> 00:06:42.610
In part, because I'm a
native Floridian, so --

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:45.810
so nobody ever puts that
together, they never quite expect

00:06:45.810 --> 00:06:48.790
that when I tell them I --
I research polar history.

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:51.850
They -- they look at me rather
strangely and I have to explain it.

00:06:51.850 --> 00:06:56.540 position:56%
And then afterwards, I actually came
across a man named John Tamplin,

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:59.750
who is medal -- was a medal
collector and researcher himself,

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:02.570
who I again, had never
met face-to-face,

00:07:02.570 --> 00:07:05.690
but we had corresponded
quite a bit over the years.

00:07:05.690 --> 00:07:10.380
At this time, John was in his early
70's and I was 36 years of age.

00:07:10.380 --> 00:07:14.810 position:56%
And I when I introduced myself,
this huge grin swept across his face

00:07:14.810 --> 00:07:18.370
and he took me by my
shoulders and shook me

00:07:18.370 --> 00:07:22.040
and exclaimed how wonderful
it was to meet me.

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:26.960
And I found out later that John
was shocked at my youth for someone

00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:30.560
who was interested in
polar exploration and --

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:32.870
and had the knowledge that
I had acquired at that time.

00:07:32.870 --> 00:07:36.650
He just couldn't believe
that I was that young.

00:07:36.650 --> 00:07:41.990
So this is -- the experiences
I've had on occasion from people

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:46.730
that I've run across over
the now almost 41 years

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:49.440
that I've been doing research.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:52.730
What I'm going to do to start off
with is I'm going to read part

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:55.140
of the preface from my book,

00:07:55.140 --> 00:07:56.470
<i>Discovering the North-West
Passage </i>.

00:07:56.470 --> 00:08:01.990
It gives you something of a --
of a overview of what I had hoped

00:08:01.990 --> 00:08:04.770
to achieve when I started
the book and of course,

00:08:04.770 --> 00:08:07.230
what I did eventually
I hope achieve.

00:08:07.230 --> 00:08:11.030
The story that follows is true.

00:08:11.030 --> 00:08:12.770
This is a balanced account

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:16.890
of the human story behind the
Four-Year Arctic Odyssey of the men

00:08:16.890 --> 00:08:20.500
of Her Majesty's ship
Investigator, during their search

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:25.060
for the missing Franklin Expedition
in the North-West Passage.

00:08:25.060 --> 00:08:28.950
Through an unfiltered lens, I have
gone to great lengths to understand

00:08:28.950 --> 00:08:33.720
and accurately depict
the events and the people

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:36.030
in which they were involved.

00:08:36.030 --> 00:08:40.440
On April 11, 1970, I stood in
amazement on a Florida beach,

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:45.570
gazing upon Apollo 13 as
she hurdled to the moon.

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:50.230
Two days later, hundreds of human
and computerized minds melded

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:53.000
in a race to save three
explorers trapped

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.470
within the frigid void of space.

00:08:56.470 --> 00:09:01.400
To the Victorian mind,
the Arctic was the moon.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:05.020
Like outer space, the Polar
Regions offer life and death.

00:09:05.020 --> 00:09:10.280
And the difference between
them hangs by a thread.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:14.480
Exploration has always been
as much about, if not more,

00:09:14.480 --> 00:09:17.590
the human species'
struggle with itself

00:09:17.590 --> 00:09:20.240
as its struggle with
the natural world.

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:25.040
With the investigators, I focused
on seeking out possibilities

00:09:25.040 --> 00:09:27.110
and then finding answers.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:30.000
In the following pages
understanding emerges

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.250
through the careful
peeling away of layers

00:09:32.250 --> 00:09:36.470
of reality these men
confronted during the expedition.

00:09:36.470 --> 00:09:40.320
As I immersed myself in
the journals, documents,

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:44.560 position:56%
and letters of the investigators and
other polar explorers of the period,

00:09:44.560 --> 00:09:47.130
their words washed over me.

00:09:47.130 --> 00:09:51.450
I delved into Naval customs,
ship construction, oceanography,

00:09:51.450 --> 00:09:56.120
ice navigation and the effects
of extreme cold and starvation

00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:00.090
on the human body, anything
that allowed me to inch closer

00:10:00.090 --> 00:10:02.330
to their 19th Century world.

00:10:02.330 --> 00:10:06.790
At the same time, I strived to
understand the indigenous peoples

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:10.120
with whom the sailors and
marines came into contact

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:14.490
and obtaining a sense of their
culture and in particular,

00:10:14.490 --> 00:10:17.280
their relationship with Europeans.

00:10:17.280 --> 00:10:23.290
What I'd like to do is give you an
overview of how this book evolved

00:10:23.290 --> 00:10:26.160
and some of the highlights, some of
the things that I actually was able

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:32.180
to discover during my research and
very much focus on the word evolve

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:38.050
because the book did change
as I wrote it and grew.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:41.920
And I was very, very pleased
with the result in that regard

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:46.170
because I was able, I think, to
bring out even a richer story

00:10:46.170 --> 00:10:49.310
than I had intended to or foresaw.

00:10:49.310 --> 00:10:53.760
And perhaps there's no better
way to begin than the end.

00:10:53.760 --> 00:10:56.410
After the book was finished
and it went to press,

00:10:56.410 --> 00:11:01.980 position:56%
I remarked to my wife one night, "If
I never write another word again,

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:05.900
it will have been worth it."

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:10.720
And a word about writing, I
think is very appropriate here.

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:16.580
I often tell people that the -- the
thing that really should be kept

00:11:16.580 --> 00:11:21.440
in mind is that I spend a lot more
time thinking about what I'm going

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.550
to write than actually writing.

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:30.250
So -- so that has really remained
uppermost in the whole process.

00:11:30.250 --> 00:11:34.780
And this along with the
self editing that I did

00:11:34.780 --> 00:11:36.580
through the whole process meant

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:40.200
that there was a tremendous
timesaving in the long run.

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:44.890
Another example is, I built my
bibliography as I went along,

00:11:44.890 --> 00:11:47.650
so I had a quick reference
myself and I was able

00:11:47.650 --> 00:11:51.710
to actually make corrections
in it at the end

00:11:51.710 --> 00:11:55.070
because I had already built a full
bibliography instead of trying

00:11:55.070 --> 00:11:57.370
to create one at that time.

00:11:58.390 --> 00:12:02.150
From the beginning, I was very
concerned about getting it right

00:12:02.150 --> 00:12:04.470
and preserving the memories
of the investigators,

00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:07.970
that was extremely important to me.

00:12:07.970 --> 00:12:11.450
I've been in contact with a lot
of descendents of the expedition

00:12:11.450 --> 00:12:15.310
and I certainly did not
want to write things

00:12:15.310 --> 00:12:18.360
that were not true
about these people.

00:12:18.360 --> 00:12:23.650 position:56%
And one of the things that I did was
I wrote a letter to the historian,

00:12:23.650 --> 00:12:27.170
David McCullough and
expressed my concern.

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:33.040
And he was very gracious in writing
back that in part, "What a fine

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:35.100
and engaging letter from you.

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:39.410
Thank you very much for your good
spirits and understanding of what's

00:12:39.410 --> 00:12:42.270
at stake in writing a book.

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:45.120
Gives me a great lift."

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.760
So from that, I thought, well, I'm
probably on the right track here.

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:51.000
I probably -- I'm probably
heading the right direction.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:56.580
So, one of the things that
really impressed me in going

00:12:56.580 --> 00:12:59.390
into this was -- or made an
impression on me I should say,

00:12:59.390 --> 00:13:03.540
is how I needed to make the writing
and the experience for the reader

00:13:03.540 --> 00:13:05.360
as authentic as possible.

00:13:05.360 --> 00:13:07.960
And in a way, what I wanted

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:12.870
to do was use the investigators
words as much as possible.

00:13:12.870 --> 00:13:16.520
And I found a lot of unpublished
material that was out there

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:19.150
and fortunately, I was
able to really go through

00:13:19.150 --> 00:13:22.150
and juxtapose all the published
and unpublished material

00:13:22.150 --> 00:13:25.810
and hopefully come up with
a really authentic idea

00:13:25.810 --> 00:13:28.820
of what occurred in
many circumstances.

00:13:28.820 --> 00:13:34.960
These are typical sailors
of the time period,

00:13:34.960 --> 00:13:41.750
although there was nobody as young
as the boy you see right here.

00:13:41.750 --> 00:13:46.730
Let's see here -- right
there, that's a boy,

00:13:46.730 --> 00:13:50.420
small boy who was not uncommon
during Victorian days aboard ship.

00:13:50.420 --> 00:13:53.220
They could be as young
as nine or ten years old.

00:13:53.220 --> 00:13:56.960
But these other sailors really
represent very typical sailors

00:13:56.960 --> 00:13:59.260
of the period.

00:14:02.710 --> 00:14:06.860
Also, these are Royal Marines from
the same time period and again,

00:14:06.860 --> 00:14:11.060
very, very typical of who you
would see except for again --

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:12.540
whoops, sorry about that,

00:14:12.540 --> 00:14:17.790
the drummer boy right
here -- the drummer boy.

00:14:17.790 --> 00:14:20.540
Now in order to do
what I set out to do

00:14:20.540 --> 00:14:23.160
