This is a naval general
service medal, which was given

00:15:46.910 --> 00:15:49.950
to Private First Class,
George Parfitt.

00:15:49.950 --> 00:15:54.530
He was one of the eight Royal
Marines who was board investigator

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:58.070
and the medal was given to
him only in the months prior

00:15:58.070 --> 00:16:00.700
to leaving for the expedition.

00:16:00.700 --> 00:16:03.790
Now, the Marines in particular
were required to wear these medals

00:16:03.790 --> 00:16:06.100
on formal occasions and since
the ship was going to be away

00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:12.170
for several years, every reason to
believe that medal was with Parfitt

00:16:12.170 --> 00:16:19.830
through the entire voyage and went
through the North-West Passage.

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:23.310
I also set about to create
individual biographies

00:16:23.310 --> 00:16:26.590
of all 66 men onboard.

00:16:26.590 --> 00:16:31.100
And in this regard, a lot of
things came to the surface.

00:16:31.100 --> 00:16:35.410
One of the things that came to
the surface is that over 39 --

00:16:35.410 --> 00:16:40.370
sorry, 39 men over -- out
of the 66 who were onboard,

00:16:40.370 --> 00:16:45.080
actually had served together in the
nine years prior to the expedition.

00:16:45.080 --> 00:16:48.110
This meant that there was a certain
unity among the crew before the

00:16:48.110 --> 00:16:52.310
expedition ever began and
that was very, very important

00:16:52.310 --> 00:16:55.150
for the cohesiveness of the ship.

00:16:55.150 --> 00:16:58.900
In assembling the biographies,
I also investigated the ships

00:16:58.900 --> 00:17:01.540
that the men had served on
before and after the expedition.

00:17:01.540 --> 00:17:07.910
I created physical profiles for
them and I even compared them

00:17:07.910 --> 00:17:11.410
by the counties from
which they were born.

00:17:11.410 --> 00:17:13.590
As you can see, many of the --

00:17:13.590 --> 00:17:18.060
many of the men actually came

00:17:18.060 --> 00:17:21.510
from the southern counties
of England here.

00:17:21.510 --> 00:17:24.640 position:56%
Now this only represents England and
Wales, there were people represented

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:28.920
from Ireland as well, and Scotland.

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:33.570
Two of the men actually
stood out in particular

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:35.720
because they were men of color.

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:38.830
They were of African descent.

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:43.830
One of them was born in England,
the other claimed to have been born

00:17:43.830 --> 00:17:49.020
in British North America or
today as we know, Canada.

00:17:49.020 --> 00:17:54.510
I looked into him much more closely
and I was able to actually come

00:17:54.510 --> 00:17:56.910
up with a good bit of
circumstantial evidence,

00:17:56.910 --> 00:18:02.710
very strong circumstantial evidence
that he wasn't Canadian at all,

00:18:02.710 --> 00:18:09.320 position:56%
he was a runaway American slave, or
at the very least, his parents were.

00:18:09.320 --> 00:18:11.550
And again, there was a lot
of circumstantial evidence

00:18:11.550 --> 00:18:13.990
that pointed to this fact.

00:18:13.990 --> 00:18:19.400
So, I was very, very pleased with
-- with that because it's very hard

00:18:19.400 --> 00:18:22.280
to actually come across
that sort of individual

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:24.060
and that sort of information.

00:18:24.060 --> 00:18:28.170
Certainly a lot of men of color
served in the Royal Navy for --

00:18:28.170 --> 00:18:32.270 position:56%
for many years throughout the years,
but to find that sort of information

00:18:32.270 --> 00:18:35.670
and connect it to a particular
individual and a particular place

00:18:35.670 --> 00:18:38.730
and time is very difficult.

00:18:38.730 --> 00:18:43.870
Now, the driving force behind the
ship was of course, the captain,

00:18:43.870 --> 00:18:47.210
Robert John Le Mesurier McClure.

00:18:47.210 --> 00:18:50.530
There were portions of his
character that can be explained

00:18:50.530 --> 00:18:56.800
in different ways and -- let
me get to him, there we go.

00:18:56.800 --> 00:19:01.330
And what is so important about
McClure is the more I looked

00:19:01.330 --> 00:19:04.520 position:56%
into his family records -- and there
were quite a few different family

00:19:04.520 --> 00:19:06.930
records from different
people throughout the years,

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.600
the more contradictions
I ran across.

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:11.660
So, I really had to
-- to work those out,

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:14.320
I had to find out what
was true and what was not.

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:17.200
And some of these things were --
were innocent things, things to --

00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:21.220
just mistakes of years, mistakes
of locations and things like that.

00:19:21.220 --> 00:19:23.760 position:56%
But it's very difficult with McClure

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:27.730
because his father died
before he was even born.

00:19:27.730 --> 00:19:31.740
He died when he was
serving in Egypt,

00:19:31.740 --> 00:19:34.720
in the early part of
the Napoleonic Wars.

00:19:34.720 --> 00:19:38.770 position:56%
So it -- it was very difficult to
come across some information in part

00:19:38.770 --> 00:19:43.600
because of that, but also because
his mother was a wife, a mother

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:45.660
and a widow all within a year.

00:19:45.660 --> 00:19:49.020
So she went through a
tremendous experience.

00:19:49.020 --> 00:19:54.820
The baby McClure was actually
given up to his godfather to raise.

00:19:54.820 --> 00:20:00.000
Now, this in and of
itself, was not unusual,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.430
but what was really
interesting was the fact

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:07.780
that McClure was the only child
of that household for many,

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:11.830
many years before his godparents
had children of their own.

00:20:11.830 --> 00:20:13.520 position:56%
I think this had a big effect on him

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:16.860
because he wasn't the
golden child anymore.

00:20:16.860 --> 00:20:20.650
And his godfather was a
former Army officer --

00:20:20.650 --> 00:20:26.130
former general, and when McClure
rejected going into an Army career

00:20:26.130 --> 00:20:29.040
and chose a naval career instead,

00:20:29.040 --> 00:20:32.120
he was behind the curve
by several years.

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:35.370
So he actually joined the
Navy at a much later age

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:38.030
in his youth than normal.

00:20:38.030 --> 00:20:42.440
So again, these things
had a cumulative effect

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:45.180
on McClure getting
ahead, making rank,

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:47.740
and progressing in a naval career.

00:20:48.770 --> 00:20:52.990
I'll read briefly from my book
and it will give you an idea

00:20:52.990 --> 00:20:56.380
about McClure's naval
environment and some of the things

00:20:56.380 --> 00:21:00.010
that had a direct impact
on the expedition.

00:21:00.010 --> 00:21:02.880
"The post-Napoleonic War
Navy was spit and polish.

00:21:02.880 --> 00:21:05.400 position:56%
And the naval officer prided himself

00:21:05.400 --> 00:21:08.040
in the keen ship handling
throughout harnessing --

00:21:08.040 --> 00:21:09.990
through harnessing the wind.

00:21:09.990 --> 00:21:13.850
McClure was caught in the midst
of this transition from sail

00:21:13.850 --> 00:21:17.250
to steam propulsion that
began in fits and starts

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:20.260
in the 1820's and 1830's.

00:21:20.260 --> 00:21:26.310
But the steam engine was an
inefficient and unsightly thing.

00:21:26.310 --> 00:21:29.410
Steam, whose grotesque
and clumsy engines,

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:32.350
whose monstrous smokestacks
there belched from --

00:21:32.350 --> 00:21:35.120
belched forth the smuts,
the constant traded mess

00:21:35.120 --> 00:21:39.160
from the combustion of filthy,
Newcastle coal and the smell --

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:42.240
first smell in contamination
of oil."

00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:48.100
So, steam was seen as an ugly
thing, something to be [inaudible].

00:21:48.100 --> 00:21:51.960
And that was the environment
that McClure knew.

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:54.750
It wasn't just McClure who
was affected, there were many,

00:21:54.750 --> 00:21:59.440
many other people, including
one of his commanding officers,

00:21:59.440 --> 00:22:02.570
who impressed this upon
McClure quite heavily.

00:22:02.570 --> 00:22:05.750
His name was John Ross.

00:22:05.750 --> 00:22:10.760
The way this played into the story
was McClure had a bitter conflict

00:22:10.760 --> 00:22:12.680
from the very start with
his second in command,

00:22:12.680 --> 00:22:14.900
Lieutenant William H. Haswell.

00:22:14.900 --> 00:22:17.350
Again, from my book.

00:22:17.350 --> 00:22:20.100
"While McClure's crewmen were
bounding through the renewal

00:22:20.100 --> 00:22:22.710
of old acquaintances,
a grave fracture

00:22:22.710 --> 00:22:25.090
in his command was taking place,

00:22:25.090 --> 00:22:27.460
threatening the ship before
she ever left England.

00:22:27.460 --> 00:22:32.120
And the problem started at the
top, during the tow down river,

00:22:32.120 --> 00:22:35.330
Lieutenant Samuel Creswell's
pen painted an ugly scene

00:22:35.330 --> 00:22:37.330
for his parents.

00:22:37.330 --> 00:22:40.210
The captain continues
to be very civil to me,

00:22:40.210 --> 00:22:44.360
but poor Haswell catches
it on every occasion.

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:47.980
Yesterday the captain went on
in a most foolish way with him,

00:22:47.980 --> 00:22:52.170
saying he should not be in this
ship, that he was incompetent

00:22:52.170 --> 00:22:57.450
to be first lieutenant, that he
would write to I don't know whom.

00:22:57.450 --> 00:23:01.430
So why did McClure insist on
humiliating his first lieutenant,

00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:05.200
a man who's support would
be crucial during the long

00:23:05.200 --> 00:23:09.960
and difficult voyage ahead by
declaring Haswell should not be

00:23:09.960 --> 00:23:13.690
in this ship and that
he was incompetent?

00:23:13.690 --> 00:23:15.590
To some degree, the
answer as wrapped

00:23:15.590 --> 00:23:18.590
up in Haswell's previous postings,

00:23:18.590 --> 00:23:23.310
the Devastation and
Penelope steamships.

00:23:24.870 --> 00:23:29.510
Haswell had served in several --
several sailing ships before this

00:23:29.510 --> 00:23:34.380
and had been successfully promoted,
but he was now well on his way

00:23:34.380 --> 00:23:37.240
to becoming Investigator's
persona non grata

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:41.850
because of the stern warnings John
Ross has repeatedly given McClure

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:47.500
against ever taking anyone with a
background in steam propulsion."

00:23:47.500 --> 00:23:50.380
So this had a tremendous
effect on the structure

00:23:50.380 --> 00:23:53.830
of the expedition again,
before it ever left England.

00:23:53.830 --> 00:23:58.470
One of the things that I was very
concerned about in my writing was

00:23:58.470 --> 00:24:01.500
to appeal to the broadest
possible audience.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:03.890
And when I say that, I'm
talking about anybody

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:06.460
from the lay person all
the way to the scholar.

00:24:06.460 --> 00:24:09.000
So bridging that gap as you were,

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:11.480
was going to be something
of a challenge.

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:15.280
And what it meant was I needed
to make the text very readable

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:17.350
and I also need to set the stage

00:24:17.350 --> 00:24:19.920
in the first two chapters
for what lay ahead.

00:24:19.920 --> 00:24:26.000
What lay ahead was a tremendous
amount of unpublished information

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:29.280
that was very detailed
and as time went on,

00:24:29.280 --> 00:24:33.480 position:56%
I realized there were certain things
that would never be understandable

00:24:33.480 --> 00:24:38.750
within that framework, so I had
to create indexes or indices

00:24:38.750 --> 00:24:41.330
in order to deal with them.

00:24:41.330 --> 00:24:46.750
One of these indices, for instance,
was the primary sources indices

00:24:46.750 --> 00:24:52.550
and this was so important because
there was a web of intrigue

00:24:52.550 --> 00:24:56.420
and unanswered questions among
the journals that I had read

00:24:56.420 --> 00:25:00.620
from the captain, from the
assistant surgeon Peers,

00:25:00.620 --> 00:25:02.660
even from the carpenter Ford.

00:25:02.660 --> 00:25:05.010
There were a lot of things
that weren't adding up,

00:25:05.010 --> 00:25:07.570
a lot of missing parts,
literally missing parts.

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:10.030
Let me give you an example.

00:25:10.030 --> 00:25:16.020
I was able to prove beyond a doubt
that McClure kept two journals.

00:25:16.020 --> 00:25:22.140
So this is a multipart
journal and there was a copy.

00:25:22.140 --> 00:25:26.430
And what happened is through
time as far as I know,

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:30.320
there's only one volume of
that journal in existence.

00:25:30.320 --> 00:25:35.010
The question comes, is that the
copy or is that the original?

00:25:35.010 --> 00:25:37.970
And this sort of thing
actually reverberated

00:25:37.970 --> 00:25:39.450
through the other journals as well,

00:25:39.450 --> 00:25:43.830
particularly the surgeon's
journal, Dr. Armstrong.

00:25:48.030 --> 00:25:51.970
I also created an index
of notable sled journeys.

00:25:51.970 --> 00:25:53.630
And the reason I did this is

00:25:53.630 --> 00:25:57.120
because when you can
attach a particular person

00:25:57.120 --> 00:26:01.090
to a particular place at a
particular time, you can track them

00:26:01.090 --> 00:26:03.970
and you can associate those
people with specific events

00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:06.830
or disassociate them
with other events.

00:26:06.830 --> 00:26:11.490
So I created an entire index so you
can go back and you can see who was

00:26:11.490 --> 00:26:15.600
where and when they were
participating in various events.

00:26:15.600 --> 00:26:20.060
These sled journeys actually
created stories within themselves

00:26:20.060 --> 00:26:23.310
because you see certain
people appear again and again.

00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:26.450
In other words, they were
favorites among the officers.

00:26:26.450 --> 00:26:30.180
This isn't unusual because there's
a certain connection that you get

00:26:30.180 --> 00:26:32.770
with someone when you
spend days, weeks,

00:26:32.770 --> 00:26:35.350
months on the sledding
trail with the same people.

00:26:35.350 --> 00:26:37.290
You get to know them,
they get to know you,

00:26:37.290 --> 00:26:40.970
you get to trust them,
they trust you.

00:26:40.970 --> 00:26:43.050
And it also played into
the story very much

00:26:43.050 --> 00:26:49.700
because Haswell being somebody who
was desperately hated by McClure,

00:26:49.700 --> 00:26:53.700
was kept out of the
picture more and more.

00:26:53.700 --> 00:26:57.040 position:56%
So he doesn't show up a lot of times
in the writings or he's referred

00:26:57.040 --> 00:27:04.390
to only slightly, sometimes
not even by name.

00:27:04.390 --> 00:27:10.910 position:56%
Several years ago, I began work on
a two-part article about this award,

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:15.190
the Arctic medal, 1818, 1855.

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:18.160
And I had intended to --
to publish it eventually,

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:21.610
but as I did the research for
the book, it became obvious

00:27:21.610 --> 00:27:26.190
that this award is
actually an integral part

00:27:26.190 --> 00:27:29.320
of the overall story, here's why.

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:34.110
The reverse of the
medal itself -- whoops.

00:27:34.110 --> 00:27:39.000
The reverse of the -- of the
actual award here was designed

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:40.580
by Samuel Creswell.

00:27:40.580 --> 00:27:43.370
And that was no mistake.

00:27:43.370 --> 00:27:48.210
Creswell had been called to
an audience of Queen Victoria

00:27:48.210 --> 00:27:50.420
and had done paintings
during the expedition

00:27:50.420 --> 00:27:51.900
and she was very impressed
with them.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:54.850
So he had an inn right there.

00:27:54.850 --> 00:28:00.400
The other thing is that Her
Majesty, Queen Victoria herself,

00:28:00.400 --> 00:28:04.190
since she was a princess, had a
great interest in exploration,

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:07.660
particularly polar exploration.

00:28:07.660 --> 00:28:13.280
And she became convinced that
the shape of the medal needed

00:28:13.280 --> 00:28:19.800
to be octagonal, not round like
war medals before and after it.

00:28:19.800 --> 00:28:21.700
So it stood out.

00:28:21.700 --> 00:28:24.070
She wanted something that
was going to stand out,

00:28:24.070 --> 00:28:27.480
it was going to be
different and recognizable.

00:28:27.480 --> 00:28:32.850
For that information, I'm very
grateful to the Royal Archives

00:28:32.850 --> 00:28:36.350
at Windsor Castle because I was
able to get special permission

00:28:36.350 --> 00:28:38.640
to actually access letters to

00:28:38.640 --> 00:28:42.670
and from Queen Victoria
on this very subject.

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:46.320
Now, for all this rich detail
and explanations and there --

00:28:46.320 --> 00:28:49.780
believe me, there's a lot more,
there's so much that's new

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:52.150
in regards to this expedition
that I have in my book.

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:54.770
I have to tell you, I'm actually
going through the book now

00:28:54.770 --> 00:28:59.600 position:56%
and making my own notes because I
-- I can't even keep up with it all,

00:28:59.600 --> 00:29:02.220
so I want to have my own
notes on some of this

00:29:02.220 --> 00:29:04.670
and where it actually
falls in the book and --

00:29:04.670 --> 00:29:07.530
and that is an ongoing process.

00:29:07.530 --> 00:29:12.100
But for all this detail and
all the richness of the story,

00:29:12.100 --> 00:29:15.150
it's important to step back and
take a look at the big picture

00:29:15.150 --> 00:29:17.070
and the big picture is this.

00:29:17.070 --> 00:29:20.570
There is no one route through
the North-West Passage,

00:29:20.570 --> 00:29:21.960
it's actually several routes.

00:29:21.960 --> 00:29:26.830
McClure discovered two of them.

00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:30.800
And through the years while these
guys were out there exploring,

00:29:30.800 --> 00:29:32.310
the ice conditions made it

00:29:32.310 --> 00:29:36.360
so that things could change
tremendously year to year.

00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:40.830 position:56%
In one year, an explorer may have a
lot of luck getting through the ice,

00:29:40.830 --> 00:29:42.220 position:56%
a lot of ways to go through the ice,

00:29:42.220 --> 00:29:45.940
and another year, be
entirely blocked.

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:49.630
So you're really at
the mercy of nature.

00:29:49.630 --> 00:29:51.290
That's very important to remember.

00:29:51.290 --> 00:29:54.580
The other thing is, no
one man can actually claim

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:56.780
to have found the North-West
Passage.

00:29:56.780 --> 00:30:01.330
McClure's experience has really
capped 30 years of experiences

00:30:01.330 --> 00:30:05.370
of many other men who
had gone before him,

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:10.950
most of them British explorers, in
finding a way through the Arctic.

00:30:10.950 --> 00:30:14.900
And during this time,
these men relied very,

00:30:14.900 --> 00:30:19.780
very heavily on native peoples
for guides and assistance.

00:30:19.780 --> 00:30:26.190
Perhaps most importantly in this
regard, McClure's experiences

00:30:26.190 --> 00:30:30.350
and those of his fellow
investigators really can be used

00:30:30.350 --> 00:30:36.480
as a yardstick and understanding
what happened to Sir John Franklin

00:30:36.480 --> 00:30:40.290
and the men of the
missing Erebus and Terror.

00:30:40.290 --> 00:30:43.520
And it is my earnest wish

00:30:43.520 --> 00:30:48.210
that my writings will be
applied to that very end.

