00:37:36.240 --> 00:37:38.330
Of course, in broad strokes,

00:37:38.330 --> 00:37:42.340
the Franklin Expedition
departed Greenhithe County Kent

00:37:42.340 --> 00:37:44.780
in England in May of 1845.

00:37:44.780 --> 00:37:49.680
With a significant fanfare and --
and seemingly justified optimism

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:55.280 position:56%
that finally this sublimely equipped
expedition would finally, you know,

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:59.880 position:56%
find the elusive North-West Passage,
something that had been the --

00:37:59.880 --> 00:38:02.270
the object of the English
mariners since Elizabethan times

00:38:02.270 --> 00:38:05.420
and the times of Frobisher
and -- and Hudson later on.

00:38:05.420 --> 00:38:11.020
And so the -- the two ships
Erebus and Terror with 129 men

00:38:11.020 --> 00:38:14.020
that ultimately entered the
Arctic, including Franklin himself.

00:38:14.020 --> 00:38:18.740 position:56%
Obviously, things didn't work out so
well and all of these men perished

00:38:18.740 --> 00:38:23.040
under certainly, rather
grim circumstances.

00:38:23.040 --> 00:38:28.260
This of course, launched -- I'll
start with the Investigator,

00:38:28.260 --> 00:38:30.220
but this launched what
is often described

00:38:30.220 --> 00:38:34.440
as the largest rescue operation
that's ever been staged

00:38:34.440 --> 00:38:35.740
in human history.

00:38:35.740 --> 00:38:39.330
Countless expeditions were
launched by the Royal Navy,

00:38:39.330 --> 00:38:43.620
privately thereafter,
American expeditions as well,

00:38:43.620 --> 00:38:48.200
to try to locate these two missing
ships and -- and the missing men.

00:38:48.200 --> 00:38:51.280
H.M.S. Investigator among its
-- amongst its claims to fame,

00:38:51.280 --> 00:38:55.410
of course, that it was part of the
first Royal Navy expedition to --

00:38:55.410 --> 00:38:58.870
to look for Franklin and his men.

00:38:58.870 --> 00:39:03.210
In fact, it was three years in
that the Admiralty, I think started

00:39:03.210 --> 00:39:07.780
to grow apprehensive as to the --
the wellbeing of the expedition

00:39:07.780 --> 00:39:10.640
and gave Clark Ross,
who actually was offered

00:39:10.640 --> 00:39:11.980
but declined the command.

00:39:11.980 --> 00:39:15.990
And probably feeling a
certain tinge of guilt perhaps,

00:39:15.990 --> 00:39:23.490 position:56%
started to develop a rescue plan
and it's under Ross's recommendation

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:26.520
that the Investigator was
purchased into the Royal Navy.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:29.230
It was actually building in
Greenock, Scotland we believe

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:30.890
as -- as a -- as a whaler.

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:34.850
And it was converted for
Arctic service and along

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:41.520
with H.M.S. Enterprise, made the
first search expedition in 1848,

00:39:41.520 --> 00:39:44.570
heavily modified to
withstand Arctic conditions.

00:39:44.570 --> 00:39:49.830
In fact, the -- also under the
supervision of William Rice,

00:39:49.830 --> 00:39:52.510
a master shipwright
in the Royal Navy --

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:56.970 position:56%
heavily reinforced with iron plating
in the bow and very thick deck beams

00:39:56.970 --> 00:40:00.150 position:56%
and all kinds of internal iron work.

00:40:00.150 --> 00:40:04.010
And so in 1848, Enterprise and
Investigator, under the command

00:40:04.010 --> 00:40:07.460
of James Clark Ross -- I think
he took it upon himself to try

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:10.410
to spearhead the -- the search.

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:13.440
They essentially followed in
the wake of Franklin essentially

00:40:13.440 --> 00:40:17.400
where he was ordered to
proceed into Lancaster Sound.

00:40:17.400 --> 00:40:21.270
And that's where they themselves
encountered impenetrable ice

00:40:21.270 --> 00:40:23.600
and they were [inaudible]
winter, the northern end

00:40:23.600 --> 00:40:25.970
of Somerset Island at Port Leopold.

00:40:25.970 --> 00:40:30.760
By the time they did send a
sledge expedition down Peel Sound

00:40:30.760 --> 00:40:33.860
and finding absolutely
no concrete trace

00:40:33.860 --> 00:40:36.660
of the Franklin party having
ventured in that direction,

00:40:36.660 --> 00:40:41.270
that may in fact have sealed the
fate of Franklin and his men.

00:40:41.270 --> 00:40:43.610
The -- given that -- it
persuaded the -- the --

00:40:43.610 --> 00:40:46.170
the Admiralty that Franklin did
not proceed in that direction

00:40:46.170 --> 00:40:47.620
and it really refocused a lot

00:40:47.620 --> 00:40:51.220
of their search efforts
farther west and -- and north.

00:40:51.220 --> 00:40:56.120
That said, Franklin was certainly
up against a ticking clock

00:40:56.120 --> 00:40:59.320
and it ultimately may have
not have made a difference.

00:40:59.320 --> 00:41:02.310
So returning to [inaudible] 1849,

00:41:02.310 --> 00:41:06.880
Investigator Enterprise were
hastily outfitted again,

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:09.340
reprovisioned for a return trip.

00:41:09.340 --> 00:41:13.160
This time anticipating as we said,

00:41:13.160 --> 00:41:15.760 position:56%
that Franklin must have made it much
farther west, they were sound --

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:20.260
sent around South America and
through the Straits of Magellan,

00:41:20.260 --> 00:41:24.300
stopping at the Sandwich Islands
where Hawaii is as Glenn mentioned.

00:41:24.300 --> 00:41:27.510
Where the -- by this time, the
two ships had been separated

00:41:27.510 --> 00:41:33.190
in a storm off of -- off of
South American and in 1850,

00:41:33.190 --> 00:41:37.620
McClure led the Investigator alone
and plunged into the Western Arctic

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:40.350
and automated into fame and infamy.

00:41:40.350 --> 00:41:43.130
So he made very steady progress

00:41:43.130 --> 00:41:46.380
in 1850 following along the
North American mainland.

00:41:46.380 --> 00:41:49.010
Again, with the explicit orders
to try to locate some trace

00:41:49.010 --> 00:41:51.240
of -- of the Franklin party.

00:41:51.240 --> 00:41:57.170
So in late 1850, they had
identified Prince of Wales Strait,

00:41:57.170 --> 00:42:01.400
one of the -- one of the arteries
of the North-West Passage now.

00:42:01.400 --> 00:42:05.700 position:56%
And sending a sledge team by October
26, they had identified the --

00:42:05.700 --> 00:42:09.480
in fact, this communicated
with this open body of water

00:42:09.480 --> 00:42:10.780
that had been surveyed

00:42:10.780 --> 00:42:12.840
by Sir William Edward
Perry many years before,

00:42:12.840 --> 00:42:17.570
identifying indeed
as a navigable route.

00:42:17.570 --> 00:42:22.320
Over wintering in the open pack,
the following navigation season,

00:42:22.320 --> 00:42:26.400
Investigator proceeded
clockwise around Banks Island

00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:29.040
and encountering treacherous
conditions such as this.

00:42:29.040 --> 00:42:34.790
This is a -- one of Left-tenant
Creswell's iconic paintings

00:42:34.790 --> 00:42:37.290
