00:46:04.360 --> 00:46:06.480
down by the head and
listing to starboard.

00:46:06.480 --> 00:46:09.990
And that convinced them that
the ship would soon flounder.

00:46:09.990 --> 00:46:15.700
So he, and his men, and the
sledge team took the opportunity

00:46:15.700 --> 00:46:18.920
to batten the hatches, but only
after removing what remained

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:22.040
of the ship's stores
that were firmly frozen

00:46:22.040 --> 00:46:23.510
in the ice in the hold.

00:46:23.510 --> 00:46:25.630
And they were added to the --

00:46:25.630 --> 00:46:30.850
the depot of stores on the
western side of Mercy Bay.

00:46:30.850 --> 00:46:34.610 position:56%
So in 2010, our team, the underwater
archaeology team working closely

00:46:34.610 --> 00:46:38.740
with our Western Arctic field unit,
undertook a fairly ambitious search

00:46:38.740 --> 00:46:41.240
for this ship in hopes that
it might be found close

00:46:41.240 --> 00:46:45.210
to where it was left
at anchor by the crew.

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:49.820
That said there were competing
possibilities, different hypothesis

00:46:49.820 --> 00:46:54.500 position:56%
as to what may have befell the
Investigator after it was abandoned.

00:46:54.500 --> 00:46:56.460
The Inuvialuit, which to say the --

00:46:56.460 --> 00:46:58.820
the indigenous people
of the Western Arctic,

00:46:58.820 --> 00:47:02.880
their reports to the Canadian
Arctic Expedition in 1915 suggested

00:47:02.880 --> 00:47:05.990
that in fact the ship had either
been broken apart on shore

00:47:05.990 --> 00:47:08.150
or that it had drifted
out into the open --

00:47:08.150 --> 00:47:10.740
open Strait and had
sank in deep water,

00:47:10.740 --> 00:47:13.400
which for us would
not be very good news.

00:47:13.400 --> 00:47:15.920
But we went to Mercy Bay anyway.

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:20.970 position:56%
And so in July, this is what -- what
the site appeared like after all

00:47:20.970 --> 00:47:23.440
of the ice had cleared from
the harbor, sort of the --

00:47:23.440 --> 00:47:24.740
from the -- from the bay.

00:47:24.740 --> 00:47:26.250
And in fact as we flew over it

00:47:26.250 --> 00:47:29.420 position:56%
for the first time it was
completely stogged with -- with ice.

00:47:29.420 --> 00:47:31.700
That's what my Newfoundland
wife would say.

00:47:31.700 --> 00:47:34.590
And so after a year of preparation,

00:47:34.590 --> 00:47:36.480
we thought that we might
not stand any chance to look

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:38.030
for it at all -- after all.

00:47:38.030 --> 00:47:43.950
But we spent some time setting up
a base camp on the western shore,

00:47:43.950 --> 00:47:48.740
slinging load after load by
helicopter from a nearby airstrip,

00:47:48.740 --> 00:47:52.920
the ominously named Polar Bear
Cabin and the northern part

00:47:52.920 --> 00:47:56.130
of Aulavik National Park.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:48:00.230
And while we readied our
Marine survey equipment

00:48:00.230 --> 00:48:02.300
and inflated our zodiac boats,

00:48:02.300 --> 00:48:06.200
a [inaudible] archaeology team
undertook a detailed study

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:09.590
of the depot or cache site
as it's generally known.

00:48:09.590 --> 00:48:11.770
This is Henry Carrie from our
Western Arctic field unit,

00:48:11.770 --> 00:48:14.530
an archeologist looking at
the most prominent feature

00:48:14.530 --> 00:48:19.870
that survived onshore from the
Investigator Expedition prior

00:48:19.870 --> 00:48:21.480
to the discovery of
the wreck site that is.

00:48:21.480 --> 00:48:25.950
And that's what -- that's what
remains of the seven tons of coal

00:48:25.950 --> 00:48:31.570 position:56%
that was landed on shore, as well as
a large scattering of barrel staves,

00:48:31.570 --> 00:48:35.060
hundreds and hundreds from the
provisions that were put there.

00:48:35.060 --> 00:48:39.720 position:56%
This is something that really speaks
not just to the nautical nature

00:48:39.720 --> 00:48:42.550
of -- of the cache, but
the fact that the -- the --

00:48:42.550 --> 00:48:47.300
the Inuvialuit made repeated
visits to Mercy Bay to make use

00:48:47.300 --> 00:48:50.680
of these materials for
upwards of 60 years it is said.

00:48:50.680 --> 00:48:54.040
And this is actually a frame from
one of the investigator's boats,

00:48:54.040 --> 00:48:58.060
from one of the ribs so to speak
of the boat, and we can tell

00:48:58.060 --> 00:49:02.500
that it's a lapstraker, a
clinker built boat given the --

00:49:02.500 --> 00:49:04.100
the edges of this frame.

00:49:04.100 --> 00:49:07.510
But every piece you'd find is
broken into links no longer than --

00:49:07.510 --> 00:49:10.300
than let's say a foot and
that's so they could harvest

00:49:10.300 --> 00:49:13.750
and extract every single copper
and iron fastener from all

00:49:13.750 --> 00:49:17.460
of these boats to assist,
you know, their --

00:49:17.460 --> 00:49:21.710
survival really, which
affected their material culture.

00:49:21.710 --> 00:49:27.280
There are many, many interesting
historical, archaeological

00:49:27.280 --> 00:49:31.760
and anthropological parallels that
can be drawn between Investigator

00:49:31.760 --> 00:49:35.920
and Franklin's ships and this
is one of them in a small way.

00:49:35.920 --> 00:49:41.240 position:56%
Right on top of the cache site faced
down was this bit of boat timber,

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:42.890
this is actually the stem
of one of the bow timber

00:49:42.890 --> 00:49:44.410
from -- from one of the boats.

00:49:44.410 --> 00:49:47.950
And as you turn it over, you can
actually see that it's engraved,

00:49:47.950 --> 00:49:50.900
there's a W that stands for the
Woolwich Dockyard, where the --

00:49:50.900 --> 00:49:53.200
the ship outfitted in 1850.

00:49:53.200 --> 00:49:56.940
A Royal Navy broad arrow mark --
this is government property mark

00:49:56.940 --> 00:49:59.840
which you'll see repeatedly in this
presentation, as well as the length

00:49:59.840 --> 00:50:03.110
of this particular
boat, likely 22 feet.

00:50:03.110 --> 00:50:06.280
This immediately reminded
us of a find made

00:50:06.280 --> 00:50:08.580
by the McClintock Expedition, 1859.

00:50:08.580 --> 00:50:11.420
All kinds of McClintock
Expedition maps

00:50:11.420 --> 00:50:14.320
and books on display here today.

00:50:14.320 --> 00:50:16.510
And by his subordinate
Left-tenant Hobson

00:50:16.510 --> 00:50:20.410
on King William Island found the
remains of one of the ship's boats

00:50:20.410 --> 00:50:25.630
from Erebus or Terror with
three skeletons in -- inside.

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:29.700 position:56%
And ultimately, the boat's stem was
recovered by the Schwatka Expedition

00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:33.380
in 1879 and now is on -- visible

00:50:33.380 --> 00:50:36.420
at the National Maritime
Museum in Greenwich, London.

00:50:36.420 --> 00:50:39.900
Here we see again, the W
for Woolwich, the date April

00:50:39.900 --> 00:50:46.060
of 1845, length of the boat.

00:50:46.060 --> 00:50:47.750
And this was actually
built by contract,

00:50:47.750 --> 00:50:51.000
it didn't have a broad arrow
mark, so this a carvel built boat,

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:55.180
which was often provided to the
Navy -- sorry, a clinker bit --

00:50:55.180 --> 00:50:57.870
built boat that was provided
to the Navy under contract

00:50:57.870 --> 00:51:00.110
because the doctors
were doing this anymore.

00:51:00.110 --> 00:51:07.840
Also the analysis of the cache
included a systematic magnetometer

00:51:07.840 --> 00:51:09.770
or walking gradiometer survey,

00:51:09.770 --> 00:51:13.940
which identified all the magnetic
anomalies from the cache --

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:18.300
hoops from the -- the [inaudible],
small nails, whatever the --

00:51:18.300 --> 00:51:21.210
the Inuvialuit didn't
-- didn't detect.

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:30.470
But also these three anomalies here
and at east of western [inaudible]

00:51:30.470 --> 00:51:34.580
of Western Ontario suspected these
might in fact represent the graves

00:51:34.580 --> 00:51:38.180
of the three investigator
crewmen who were not rescued.

00:51:38.180 --> 00:51:42.650
We know their names, John
Boyle, John Ames and John Kerr,

00:51:42.650 --> 00:51:47.440
who also come to scurvy just before
the -- the Resolute rescued them.

00:51:47.440 --> 00:51:51.770
And actually John Moore,
my colleague in the unit --

00:51:51.770 --> 00:51:53.070
oddly enough, he was
eating a lot more --

00:51:53.070 --> 00:51:57.940
more oranges, not wanting to suffer
the curse of Johns in Mercy Bay.

00:51:57.940 --> 00:52:02.810
And ultimately, if you go exact to
that point on the magnetometer map,

00:52:02.810 --> 00:52:05.600
well, you see them,
these outlines of --

00:52:05.600 --> 00:52:10.390 position:56%
of three graves where the permafrost
has not slumped because it's held

00:52:10.390 --> 00:52:15.320
up by a coffin, these are
coffin shaped outlines,

00:52:15.320 --> 00:52:20.310
which makes us think of the three
Beechey Island graves that were

00:52:20.310 --> 00:52:23.240
from the H.M.S. Erebus
and the Terror.

00:52:23.240 --> 00:52:29.230
So as the [inaudible] team did
their work, we took to our --

00:52:29.230 --> 00:52:33.080
our 19 foot zodiac and conducted a
towed side scan sonar survey to try

00:52:33.080 --> 00:52:35.310
to locate the wreck site.

00:52:35.310 --> 00:52:38.060
And in contrast to what you'll see
with the search for Erebus later

00:52:38.060 --> 00:52:40.770
in this presentation, this
actually went very, very quickly.

00:52:40.770 --> 00:52:45.510
And after a year of
preparation and the effort

00:52:45.510 --> 00:52:46.890
of getting all this equipment to --

00:52:46.890 --> 00:52:49.710
to the Arctic, ultimately
it took us three minutes

00:52:49.710 --> 00:52:51.030
to locate this wreck site.

00:52:51.030 --> 00:52:54.470
I wish it was always that -- that
easy and it certainly is not.

00:52:54.470 --> 00:52:57.430
But this is one of the
earlier images, the showing --

00:52:57.430 --> 00:53:01.410 position:56%
showing the Investigator wreck site,
this being the stern and the bow.

00:53:01.410 --> 00:53:05.640
We could tell right away that it
was in remarkably sound condition,

00:53:05.640 --> 00:53:08.910
still preserved to, really to the
height of -- of the weather deck,

00:53:08.910 --> 00:53:11.310
the upper deck, although
impacted by the ice.

00:53:11.310 --> 00:53:14.460
And you see ice scouring all
about the perimeter of the site.

00:53:14.460 --> 00:53:19.230
And this is a little sketch by --
by John, showing the ice conditions

00:53:19.230 --> 00:53:21.210
and we weren't really even
intending to survey that day,

00:53:21.210 --> 00:53:23.230
we were just testing the
equipment because the --

00:53:23.230 --> 00:53:25.670
the bay was still solidly
full of ice.

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:29.180
We just had this small serpentine
route that we could follow

00:53:29.180 --> 00:53:31.620
to test the equipment and that just
happened to be exactly where --

00:53:31.620 --> 00:53:34.620
where the wreck was located
and generally very close

00:53:34.620 --> 00:53:40.300 position:56%
to where Frederick Cravay pinpointed
it for us kindly enough in 1854.

00:53:40.300 --> 00:53:44.030
So it was a follow -- it was
another year before we can return

00:53:44.030 --> 00:53:46.580
to the wreck site of the
Investigator to dive it,

00:53:46.580 --> 00:53:51.900
a very long year for us in the unit
to waiting within anticipation.

00:53:51.900 --> 00:53:54.420
And the -- just an
extraordinary experience

00:53:54.420 --> 00:53:57.860
of diving a pristine
shipwreck site this far north,

00:53:57.860 --> 00:54:01.850
at 74 degrees northern latitude.

00:54:01.850 --> 00:54:04.850
And only when you see it
up -- up close can you --

00:54:04.850 --> 00:54:07.810
can you really appreciate
just the magnitude of it,

00:54:07.810 --> 00:54:09.850
but really just how
well preserved it is.

00:54:09.850 --> 00:54:14.460
This is a close up looking at
the stern and the entire hull

00:54:14.460 --> 00:54:17.170
of the ship is clad with
copper because the ship went

00:54:17.170 --> 00:54:20.290
around South America through
the Tropics, stopping at Hawaii,

00:54:20.290 --> 00:54:25.700
it was clad in copper to deter ship
boring teredo navalis, a shipworm

00:54:25.700 --> 00:54:28.170
and gribble and that sort of
thing, which would eat the wood.

00:54:28.170 --> 00:54:31.240
And we could still see the copper
and draft marks, which here shows

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:35.150
that we're 12 feet above -- above
the keel and the [inaudible] upon

00:54:35.150 --> 00:54:36.450
which the rudder would have --

00:54:36.450 --> 00:54:40.630
the hinges essentially that
the rudder would have swung on.

00:54:40.630 --> 00:54:46.270
So we had a very productive time,
we made over 100 dives on the site

00:54:46.270 --> 00:54:50.340
or nine intense day of diving,
often diving until 4 o'clock

00:54:50.340 --> 00:54:51.640
in the morning because
at this time of --

00:54:51.640 --> 00:54:53.450
of the summer, we enjoyed
perpetual daylight.

00:54:53.450 --> 00:54:56.460
And here we're inserting
a high definition point

00:54:56.460 --> 00:54:59.310
of view inspection camera into the
nooks and crannies below the decks,

00:54:59.310 --> 00:55:02.570
trying to identify what
spaces would preserve their

00:55:02.570 --> 00:55:04.390
archeological integrity.

00:55:04.390 --> 00:55:07.830
Ultimately what we found is that
the entire ship was silted --

00:55:07.830 --> 00:55:11.150
silted in, which was disappointing
in a way, but actually bodes very,

00:55:11.150 --> 00:55:15.870 position:56%
very well for the preservation of --
of materials down in the lower deck.

00:55:15.870 --> 00:55:19.650
And here we see the 20 odd
cabins for the ship's officers

00:55:19.650 --> 00:55:23.430 position:56%
and including the great cabin for --

00:55:23.430 --> 00:55:28.930
for McClure in the stern with
Haswell and Creswell and Armstrong

00:55:28.930 --> 00:55:31.240
and -- and everyone else.

00:55:31.240 --> 00:55:35.780
And we think that many of these
spaces will actually survive intact

00:55:35.780 --> 00:55:39.580
representing small time capsules,
representing the shipboard life

00:55:39.580 --> 00:55:41.750
of those specific individuals
which is very exciting

00:55:41.750 --> 00:55:44.130
for us as archaeologists.

00:55:44.130 --> 00:55:46.040
And then deeper down into
the bows of the ship,

00:55:46.040 --> 00:55:47.340
beyond what we can glimpse,

00:55:47.340 --> 00:55:52.420
certainly there's just enormous
potential, the botanical

00:55:52.420 --> 00:55:54.050
and biological samples
that are preserved,

00:55:54.050 --> 00:55:57.240
probably with their labels even
intact down in the bread room,

00:55:57.240 --> 00:56:02.620
whatever would perhaps remain in
the spirits locker down below.

00:56:02.620 --> 00:56:06.950
But other structures like Mr.
Sylvester's patent heating

00:56:06.950 --> 00:56:09.650
apparatus, a coal fired heater

00:56:09.650 --> 00:56:11.890
for warming the ship
in Arctic conditions.

00:56:11.890 --> 00:56:16.350
And we had enough time
to have a good look

00:56:16.350 --> 00:56:19.410
and to recover a certain
number of representative

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:22.330
and diagnostic artifacts, not
sure you can see it in this light,

00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:26.300
but the entire site is
covered by a thin lens of silt.

00:56:26.300 --> 00:56:29.640
Here you see the outline of a --

00:56:29.640 --> 00:56:34.290
of a boot, which upon recovery you
can see is a typical square toed

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:39.020
Arctic sea service boot
very, very much like finds

00:56:39.020 --> 00:56:41.310
that have been contributed
to the Erebus and the Terror.

00:56:41.310 --> 00:56:46.540
This Arctic boot from Starvation
Cove where the final survivors

00:56:46.540 --> 00:56:50.450
at that time succumbed we believe.

00:56:50.450 --> 00:56:52.850
And really demonstrating
just the very close parallels

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:57.240
and material culture
that we stand to identify

00:56:57.240 --> 00:57:00.730
between the two shipwreck sites.

00:57:00.730 --> 00:57:04.580 position:56%
Probably the most [inaudible] fact
that was recovered from Investigator

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:10.220
in 2011, and you can just see
it as it was lying in situ,

00:57:10.220 --> 00:57:14.210
there's the trigger
and over here the --

00:57:14.210 --> 00:57:20.790
the butt plate for this very
well preserved 1839 pattern,

00:57:20.790 --> 00:57:22.160
procession-sidewall musket.

00:57:22.160 --> 00:57:26.350
Which we carefully wrapped up and
were able to recover to the surface

00:57:26.350 --> 00:57:30.830
and now it's in conservation
treatment at our labs in Ottawa.

00:57:30.830 --> 00:57:34.910
And again, we can find close
parallels to this sort of firearm

00:57:34.910 --> 00:57:37.570
in the relic collection at
the National Maritime Museum.

00:57:37.570 --> 00:57:40.290
From all these implements
from the Erebus and Terror

00:57:40.290 --> 00:57:43.520
that were recovered by the
Inuit and ultimately purchased

00:57:43.520 --> 00:57:45.290
by various search parties
in the mid-19th Century.

00:57:45.290 --> 00:57:52.480
In fact, the -- the brass tang
plate on this particular firearm is

00:57:52.480 --> 00:57:54.660
so well preserved, it
preserves a lot number or a --

00:57:54.660 --> 00:57:55.960
or perhaps even a serial number.

00:57:55.960 --> 00:58:01.650
The date likely of assembly in 1842
and a WXD, which during this period

00:58:01.650 --> 00:58:03.750
of time, actually stands

00:58:03.750 --> 00:58:05.890
for the Woolwich Division
of the Royal Marines.

00:58:05.890 --> 00:58:09.970
So we can actually attribute this
particular firearm to the handful

00:58:09.970 --> 00:58:11.810
of Royal Marines that
were garrisoned to --

00:58:11.810 --> 00:58:16.620
to Investigator for this
second Arctic voyage.

00:58:16.620 --> 00:58:20.320
So in broad strokes, of course,
we can see the progress of --

00:58:20.320 --> 00:58:23.150
of the investigators
where they overwintered,

00:58:23.150 --> 00:58:28.900
ultimately where the ship
was abandoned in 1853.

00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:31.330
And they made their way
across the North-West Passage,

00:58:31.330 --> 00:58:33.020
ultimately largely on foot.

00:58:33.020 --> 00:58:36.830
As the Resolute and the Intrepid
were ordered to be abandoned

00:58:36.830 --> 00:58:38.330
when they got trapped
on the ice by --

00:58:38.330 --> 00:58:41.840
by Commander Belcher off of
Cape Covern [assumed spelling],

00:58:41.840 --> 00:58:46.940 position:56%
but eventually they all piled onto
a small number of transport vessels,

00:58:46.940 --> 00:58:50.720
including the H.M.S. North Star
and made their way back home again.

00:58:50.720 --> 00:58:52.950
So discovering the
North-West Passage,

00:58:52.950 --> 00:58:57.420
but also affecting the first
European, let's say, transit.

00:58:57.420 --> 00:59:00.460
Although largely on
foot and in the process,

00:59:00.460 --> 00:59:02.520
really the first circumnavigation
of all of north

00:59:02.520 --> 00:59:05.520
and South America at the same time.

00:59:05.520 --> 00:59:08.190
Here of course, is the
reconstructive route taken

00:59:08.190 --> 00:59:12.910
by the Franklin party just to
change gears, which obviously ends

00:59:12.910 --> 00:59:17.620
in a dead end here off of
-- of King William Island.

00:59:17.620 --> 00:59:20.880
Where the two ships, Erebus and
Terror, are last seen by whalers

00:59:20.880 --> 00:59:24.960
in Baffin Bay, where they first
overwintered in 1845 to 1846 off

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:27.070
of Beechey Island, where
those three graves from --

00:59:27.070 --> 00:59:29.490
from that party are located.

00:59:29.490 --> 00:59:31.830
And the following navigation
season 1846,

00:59:31.830 --> 00:59:36.530
we believe they descended Peel
Sound, were beset in ice or trapped

00:59:36.530 --> 00:59:41.280
in ice, the grip of which would
not release these two ships

00:59:41.280 --> 00:59:43.320
for the following two years.

00:59:43.320 --> 00:59:49.040
So we know from this rather
iconic [inaudible] note that's now

00:59:49.040 --> 00:59:53.040
on display at the National Maritime
Museum in Greenwich, which tells us

00:59:53.040 --> 00:59:57.800 position:56%
until the discovery really of the
Erebus wreck site of really the most

00:59:57.800 --> 01:00:02.170
of what we -- we know at
least from European sources.

01:00:02.170 --> 01:00:06.410
So in this note, this is kind of
a terse form letter that announced

01:00:06.410 --> 01:00:07.730
that things were going
reasonably well.

01:00:07.730 --> 01:00:14.020
In 1847, where they overwintered ,
was signed by Left-tenant Gram Gore

01:00:14.020 --> 01:00:19.760
of -- of the Erebus, but they
return to this note a year later

01:00:19.760 --> 01:00:23.890
and left a far more chilling
account in the marginalia.

01:00:23.890 --> 01:00:30.500
This signed now by a -- by
Captain Crozier of H.M.S. Terror

01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:31.880
who now had assumed the --

01:00:31.880 --> 01:00:34.170
the command of the overall
expedition announces

01:00:34.170 --> 01:00:37.060
in typically terse
Royal Navy style that --

01:00:37.060 --> 01:00:39.620
that Franklin had died
the previous year

01:00:39.620 --> 01:00:42.200
and they don't bother
to say why or how.

01:00:42.200 --> 01:00:43.500
And announced their intention

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:45.990
to desert the two ships
five leagues northwest --

01:00:45.990 --> 01:00:50.030
north north west of this point,
giving us sort of a last report

01:00:50.030 --> 01:00:52.550
of position of where
the ships were last seen

01:00:52.550 --> 01:00:56.250
by their European cruise,
supposedly.

01:00:56.250 --> 01:00:58.730
And that's really where
the historical record ends

01:00:58.730 --> 01:01:00.880
when it comes to Erebus and Terror.

01:01:00.880 --> 01:01:05.020
So what we had to rely
on archaeologically

01:01:05.020 --> 01:01:08.630
in the search was a
corpus of Inuit's testimony

01:01:08.630 --> 01:01:13.210
from mid-19th Century that
was recorded by a succession

01:01:13.210 --> 01:01:17.660
of search parties and including
McClintock we mentioned, in 1859,

01:01:17.660 --> 01:01:21.900
10 years later, Charles Francis
Hall, an American publisher

01:01:21.900 --> 01:01:25.150
who felt he was on a mission
from God to -- to save these men.

01:01:25.150 --> 01:01:28.180
Ten years late -- sorry,
10 years after McClintock

01:01:28.180 --> 01:01:30.540
and certainly 20 years too late.

01:01:30.540 --> 01:01:35.330
And Frederick Schwatka, a U.S.
Army cavalry officer who was --

01:01:35.330 --> 01:01:39.450
in around 1879 who
probably maintained no hope

01:01:39.450 --> 01:01:41.140
of actually finding survivors,

01:01:41.140 --> 01:01:43.240
but the hope that they
might find some --

01:01:43.240 --> 01:01:46.170
some telling, written record.

01:01:46.170 --> 01:01:49.610
So, all of this evidence is
kind of [inaudible] captured

01:01:49.610 --> 01:01:52.330
in this UK Admiralty chart --

01:01:52.330 --> 01:01:58.190
chart 5101, which in red shows
observations of skeletal remains,

01:01:58.190 --> 01:02:02.070 position:56%
the -- the sun bleached bones of the
Franklin crew as -- as they are --

01:02:02.070 --> 01:02:04.290
now are strewed across
the landscape.

01:02:04.290 --> 01:02:07.080
But in blue, and this is
all color coded and --

01:02:07.080 --> 01:02:09.290
and mentioned in the legend,
which I've dropped off here

01:02:09.290 --> 01:02:13.550
for display purposes, but the
blue is the Inuit accounts

01:02:13.550 --> 01:02:14.980
and actually specifically
says in the --

01:02:14.980 --> 01:02:17.950
in legend that they're not
inherently trustworthy given

01:02:17.950 --> 01:02:19.250
the source.

01:02:19.250 --> 01:02:23.430
Ironically, with benefit of
hindsight, we now see that in fact,

01:02:23.430 --> 01:02:28.130
it was Inuit testimony
that was instrumental in --

01:02:28.130 --> 01:02:29.800
in our ability to locate the wreck

01:02:29.800 --> 01:02:34.860
of H.M.S. Erebus just the
last September in 2014.

01:02:34.860 --> 01:02:38.470 position:56%
Let this shows two possible
trajectories for on one of the ships

01:02:38.470 --> 01:02:43.020
that end up in the -- the southern
Queen [inaudible] Gulf area.

01:02:43.020 --> 01:02:46.180
The Inuit's suggest that
the fate of the two ships

01:02:46.180 --> 01:02:48.890
after they're abandoned
somehow parted ways.

01:02:48.890 --> 01:02:51.350
That one of the ships
somehow made it farther south,

01:02:51.350 --> 01:02:55.630
the other ship sunk earlier
on in deeper water, they claim

01:02:55.630 --> 01:02:59.100
and that they weren't able
harvest any materials from it.

01:02:59.100 --> 01:03:06.180 position:56%
So we've been looking for both -- in
both areas since 2008 and by 2014,

01:03:06.180 --> 01:03:10.600
we had amassed over 1200 square --
actually, 1400 square kilometers

01:03:10.600 --> 01:03:15.030
of side scan sonar coverage, an
area significantly larger even

01:03:15.030 --> 01:03:19.590
in the area of Los
Angeles, substantial area.

01:03:19.590 --> 01:03:24.970 position:56%
Typically using this tool as the
mainstay of our toolbox in searching

01:03:24.970 --> 01:03:29.420
for shipwreck targets, this is
a toad side scan sonar system,

01:03:29.420 --> 01:03:34.200 position:56%
which produces acoustic two
dimensional images of the sea floor,

01:03:34.200 --> 01:03:38.260
identifying superpose objects
including hopefully shipwrecks.

01:03:38.260 --> 01:03:43.740
So, over the course of six years,
towing a side scan sonar system all

01:03:43.740 --> 01:03:46.680
over the place and staring at
the monotonous flow of the data

01:03:46.680 --> 01:03:49.850
down the sonar screen,
something called a waterfall.

01:03:49.850 --> 01:03:52.830
We had not encountered
a single solitary trace

01:03:52.830 --> 01:03:54.710
of anything cultural,
not a log, nothing.

01:03:54.710 --> 01:03:58.150
It is a very barren
landscape, at least to our eyes

01:03:58.150 --> 01:04:02.050
and there was just
nothing, no promising leads.

01:04:02.050 --> 01:04:07.300
Finally in 2014, we
actually caught a break

01:04:07.300 --> 01:04:09.560
and actually our trustworthy
archaeology counterparts have been

01:04:09.560 --> 01:04:12.850
working with us side
by side since 2008 --

01:04:12.850 --> 01:04:17.220
came across this object
during their effort to set

01:04:17.220 --> 01:04:20.070
up a GPS reference station
with our hydrographic service

01:04:20.070 --> 01:04:21.570
on a nearby island.

01:04:21.570 --> 01:04:25.710
And the helicopter pilot, Andrew
Sterling, came across this object,

01:04:25.710 --> 01:04:27.740
which was brought back to the ship

01:04:27.740 --> 01:04:29.580
and pretty quickly
we were actually able

01:04:29.580 --> 01:04:32.570
to identify what specifically
it -- it represented.

01:04:32.570 --> 01:04:34.040
And I don't think you can
see it in this lighting,

01:04:34.040 --> 01:04:36.390
but there are two broad arrow marks

01:04:36.390 --> 01:04:40.080
of these ubiquitous
government property marks

01:04:40.080 --> 01:04:44.460
that clearly told us this object
came from one of Franklin's ships.

01:04:44.460 --> 01:04:48.980
There are only so many Royal Navy
ships sunk in the area after all.

01:04:48.980 --> 01:04:52.780 position:56%
And in consultation with the ship's
plans of Erebus and Terror, in fact,

01:04:52.780 --> 01:04:54.620
it is only a couple
of hours before John,

01:04:54.620 --> 01:04:57.510
he was able to decipher
what exactly this was.

01:04:57.510 --> 01:05:01.070
And that was a lower pintle,
the anchor point for one

01:05:01.070 --> 01:05:05.280
of the ship's davits for deploying
and recovering the ship's boats

01:05:05.280 --> 01:05:10.950
over the quarter -- the
string quarters of the ship.

01:05:10.950 --> 01:05:15.490
So this also told us that a large,
heavy iron object likely indicated

01:05:15.490 --> 01:05:17.190
that a wreck was close at hand.

01:05:17.190 --> 01:05:19.820
Something that the Inuit
[inaudible] who had cached

01:05:19.820 --> 01:05:22.520
that behind a large boulder would
not want to carry with them all

01:05:22.520 --> 01:05:26.300
across the Arctic, being rather
heavy and not terribly useful.

01:05:26.300 --> 01:05:29.770 position:56%
So it appears that they broke off
the pintle end and probably fastened

01:05:29.770 --> 01:05:34.290
that into something useful, and
then dumped it where it was found.

01:05:34.290 --> 01:05:38.050
So excitedly the next day
we took to the water again

01:05:38.050 --> 01:05:41.830
and shifted our survey area
a little bit to the east.

01:05:41.830 --> 01:05:44.700
And with our survey vessel,

01:05:44.700 --> 01:05:47.280
the [inaudible] research
vessel investigator,

01:05:47.280 --> 01:05:51.910
where H.M.S. Investigator was
unsuccessful in locating any sign

01:05:51.910 --> 01:05:54.700
of the ship's investigator, the --

01:05:54.700 --> 01:05:59.870
the second got lucky
on September 2, 2014.

01:05:59.870 --> 01:06:03.630
And under absolutely
sublime surveying conditions,

01:06:03.630 --> 01:06:07.700
at long last we found
the first images

01:06:07.700 --> 01:06:09.680
and it was absolutely unmistakable

01:06:09.680 --> 01:06:10.980
when it first appeared
on the screen.

01:06:10.980 --> 01:06:16.080
This is actually a few passes later
after we approached it differently,

01:06:16.080 --> 01:06:21.920
but just the cathartic,
you know, release --

01:06:21.920 --> 01:06:28.360
relief really, that after six years
of searching with growing comments

01:06:28.360 --> 01:06:31.850
from the -- the media that,
why were we wasting our time,

01:06:31.850 --> 01:06:35.010
suggestions that even if we found
something, it would be nothing

01:06:35.010 --> 01:06:36.370
but toothpicks on the bottom.

01:06:36.370 --> 01:06:37.670
Why were you bothering?

01:06:37.670 --> 01:06:42.130
Finally, this remarkably intact
Royal Navy shipwreck appeared

01:06:42.130 --> 01:06:43.430
on our screen.

01:06:43.430 --> 01:06:45.010
At this time, we didn't
know which ship it was,

01:06:45.010 --> 01:06:46.470
that would take quite
a bit of research

01:06:46.470 --> 01:06:49.560
as subsequent investigation.

01:06:49.560 --> 01:06:52.310
But from the initial sonar
images, we're able to tell

01:06:52.310 --> 01:06:55.310
that it was intact again, to the
-- the height of the weather deck,

01:06:55.310 --> 01:06:59.180
that it was standing given the
acoustic shadow, a full four

01:06:59.180 --> 01:07:01.380
and a half or five meters
proud of the seafloor.

01:07:01.380 --> 01:07:04.510 position:56%
And we could actually see telltale
signs of the Royal Navy modification

01:07:04.510 --> 01:07:06.000
for Arctic service, so we --

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:09.740
we were absolutely convinced that
was the ship we were looking for,

01:07:09.740 --> 01:07:12.410
as if there's much doubt.

01:07:12.410 --> 01:07:15.660 position:56%
So excitedly after the announcements
made by our prime minister,

01:07:15.660 --> 01:07:18.760
in Ottawa we were all
sent back to the site

01:07:18.760 --> 01:07:22.790
and our entire dive team deployed
and excitedly made the first dives

01:07:22.790 --> 01:07:26.980
on the wreck of -- of the --
well, we now know it to be Erebus.

01:07:26.980 --> 01:07:30.690
But I would certainly describe
as the most remarkable sensation

01:07:30.690 --> 01:07:31.990
of my professional career.

01:07:31.990 --> 01:07:33.290
There's no doubt about that.

01:07:33.290 --> 01:07:34.920
As everywhere, your eyes were dark,

01:07:34.920 --> 01:07:36.710
there's something remarkable
just lying there,

01:07:36.710 --> 01:07:38.610
tucked in amongst the
collapsed timbers.

01:07:38.610 --> 01:07:42.060
And it was one of the first
things you could see are these two

01:07:42.060 --> 01:07:45.450
beautiful brass six
pounder canon just lying

01:07:45.450 --> 01:07:49.070
on the seafloor right
stern of -- of the wreck.

01:07:49.070 --> 01:07:54.230
And this is something I find
interesting is someone who's

01:07:54.230 --> 01:07:55.770 position:56%
interested in -- in steam propulsion

01:07:55.770 --> 01:07:59.840
in the Royal Navy in
the mid-19th Century.

01:07:59.840 --> 01:08:04.020
This is the outer stern post
and the inner stern post

01:08:04.020 --> 01:08:05.320
to get excessively tactical,

01:08:05.320 --> 01:08:09.570
but you'll see these cast bronze
railings, these are tracks

01:08:09.570 --> 01:08:13.910
that actually allowed the ship's
two bladed propeller to be lowered

01:08:13.910 --> 01:08:15.490
into position and then
retracted again.

01:08:15.490 --> 01:08:19.770
The Erebus and the Terror were
the first ships to be outfitted

01:08:19.770 --> 01:08:21.280
with a steam driven screw propeller

01:08:21.280 --> 01:08:23.410
for the purposes of
polar navigation.

01:08:23.410 --> 01:08:25.870
And so, we're very interested
in studying this as --

01:08:25.870 --> 01:08:30.140
this time Marines -- the Marine's
steam power was still very much

01:08:30.140 --> 01:08:31.530
at its infancy.

01:08:31.530 --> 01:08:34.890
And here you can actually see the
-- the tracks and the little slot,

01:08:34.890 --> 01:08:38.650
this is where the propeller shaft
would've -- would've rotated.

01:08:38.650 --> 01:08:42.580
And we have, of course, the
reference from the ship's plans,

01:08:42.580 --> 01:08:43.920
the National Maritime Museum,

01:08:43.920 --> 01:08:47.380
and this shows this rather crude
looking two bladed propeller,

01:08:47.380 --> 01:08:48.870
they didn't even have
the terminology set yet.

01:08:48.870 --> 01:08:52.640 position:56%
They called it the -- the fan blades
of the -- of the -- of the screw.

01:08:52.640 --> 01:08:56.480
And this does detail what both
the tracks, but the mechanism

01:08:56.480 --> 01:08:58.650
that they would -- they would --

01:08:58.650 --> 01:09:00.960
when retracted, they would
lower these chalks wooden

01:09:00.960 --> 01:09:03.680
and access the tank,
to stop up the plate --

01:09:03.680 --> 01:09:06.830
the space because they wouldn't
want the ice to get a purchase

01:09:06.830 --> 01:09:10.010
on where the propeller was
and -- and rip the stern off.

01:09:10.010 --> 01:09:14.650
And we actually have referenced
this interesting sketch

01:09:14.650 --> 01:09:18.280
by Left-tenant Irving
from the expedition,

01:09:18.280 --> 01:09:21.270
actually during their dispatches
sent home from Greenland.

01:09:21.270 --> 01:09:25.760
And in a letter to his sister,
Katie, he, you know, shows a sketch

01:09:25.760 --> 01:09:27.920
and this is one of the
-- the steam engines.

01:09:27.920 --> 01:09:29.540
And worth mentioning, of course,

01:09:29.540 --> 01:09:31.940
these were not purpose-built
Marine steam engines,

01:09:31.940 --> 01:09:36.100
they were adapted locomotive
engines from the Greenwich Railway.

01:09:36.100 --> 01:09:38.940 position:56%
Basically dropped into the aft hold,
turned sideways and with the --

01:09:38.940 --> 01:09:40.720
the wheels removed to
drop the propeller shaft,

01:09:40.720 --> 01:09:43.790
so really, really interesting.

01:09:43.790 --> 01:09:48.390 position:56%
Something that is interesting about
both ships again, is that they're --

01:09:48.390 --> 01:09:52.060
they represent these
rather unique repositories

01:09:52.060 --> 01:09:55.810
of a very obscure Victorian
industrial technology.

01:09:55.810 --> 01:09:59.010
These are the ships
main bilge pumps,

01:09:59.010 --> 01:10:03.120
these are patented Massey double
action lift and force bilge pumps.

01:10:03.120 --> 01:10:07.310 position:56%
Something you can't find anywhere
else in the world, you can't even go

01:10:07.310 --> 01:10:10.020
to the science museum and --
and see what these look like

01:10:10.020 --> 01:10:12.980
and how they operate, really
we only have recourse done

01:10:12.980 --> 01:10:15.450 position:56%
through the -- our archaeology here.

01:10:15.450 --> 01:10:16.840
There is a close up of
the -- these are the --

01:10:16.840 --> 01:10:21.040
the pump heads to be turned
with a big bell crank to --

01:10:21.040 --> 01:10:24.480
to siphon the water
out of the ship's hold.

01:10:24.480 --> 01:10:28.270
They wanted to outfit
these ships with the --

01:10:28.270 --> 01:10:31.300
the most capable technology
available given the difficulty

01:10:31.300 --> 01:10:34.340
of the task that was hand to them.

01:10:34.340 --> 01:10:36.050
So this is a plan of
the upper deck of --

01:10:36.050 --> 01:10:42.930
of the Erebus, trying
to build pumps there.

01:10:42.930 --> 01:10:46.040
And these illuminators
or deck prisms

01:10:46.040 --> 01:10:48.990
that would filter ambient
light below decks

01:10:48.990 --> 01:10:52.900
to make the place a bit more
hospitable during the long

01:10:52.900 --> 01:10:54.290
winter months.

01:10:54.290 --> 01:10:59.030
And this is actually kind
of hard to see I got to say,

01:10:59.030 --> 01:11:03.010
but here I'm actually looking
through a deck combing,

01:11:03.010 --> 01:11:05.750
so right on top of
the -- the upper deck.

01:11:05.750 --> 01:11:09.360
This is a skylight that would've
been situated directly over top

01:11:09.360 --> 01:11:14.430 position:56%
of the -- the ward room, so I can
imagine the sailors casually walking

01:11:14.430 --> 01:11:16.830
by here and eavesdropping
conversations just below here

01:11:16.830 --> 01:11:20.200
between the senior
officers, where probably a lot

01:11:20.200 --> 01:11:23.490
of significant decisions were
-- were -- were mulled over.

01:11:23.490 --> 01:11:27.600
And this is the -- something
we don't commonly see on --

01:11:27.600 --> 01:11:29.650
on shipwrecks, certainly in Canada.

01:11:29.650 --> 01:11:33.350
This is the ship's tiller, but
it's actually solid bronze,

01:11:33.350 --> 01:11:35.470
usually be something
made out of wood.

01:11:35.470 --> 01:11:38.770
And there's the end of its
12 feet long and this is

01:11:38.770 --> 01:11:40.070
where we would notch
into the rudder.

01:11:40.070 --> 01:11:41.840
Essentially this is a big
beam that allowed the --

01:11:41.840 --> 01:11:43.540
the rudder to articulate.

01:11:43.540 --> 01:11:46.690
It's bronze, we think,
because the --

01:11:46.690 --> 01:11:50.010 position:56%
the ship's hull was lengthened to
accommodate the propeller, so now --

01:11:50.010 --> 01:11:52.650
all of a sudden the rudder's now
at several feet farther raft,

01:11:52.650 --> 01:11:55.840
so they need a really strong
rudder, this is maneuvered

01:11:55.840 --> 01:11:57.720
by the ship's helm, the
tiller -- or the wheel.

01:11:57.720 --> 01:12:01.270
So they -- like many features of
these ships, they are heavily,

01:12:01.270 --> 01:12:04.110
heavily overbuilt to
withstand Arctic conditions.

01:12:04.110 --> 01:12:08.780
The -- certainly the
most iconic artifacts

01:12:08.780 --> 01:12:12.190
that we encountered right away,
on actually the very first dive,

01:12:12.190 --> 01:12:17.900
this is the ship's bell, the
only artifact we recovered

01:12:17.900 --> 01:12:20.740
in the first series
of dives in September.

01:12:20.740 --> 01:12:26.600
And again, it's emblazed into the
-- or embossed actually with the --

01:12:26.600 --> 01:12:28.160
the Royal Navy broad arrow.

01:12:28.160 --> 01:12:31.130
And very conveniently, the
date 1845 that would --

01:12:31.130 --> 01:12:33.130
archaeology should always
be that straightforward.

01:12:33.130 --> 01:12:40.380 position:56%
So quickly, we wanted to get back to
the site, we only had two days to --

01:12:40.380 --> 01:12:44.130
to reconnoiter the site before the
-- the season ended in September,

01:12:44.130 --> 01:12:47.780
so we went back with our Department
of National Defense in April.

01:12:47.780 --> 01:12:50.900
As you could see, it's solid
ice in this point in time.

01:12:50.900 --> 01:12:55.890
And the Department of National
Defense set up an ice camp

01:12:55.890 --> 01:12:59.840
for about 50 people right
over top of the wreck site.

01:12:59.840 --> 01:13:06.310
And by boring these large holes,
we're able to dive through the ice

01:13:06.310 --> 01:13:09.890
and access the wreck under
very, very stable conditions.

01:13:09.890 --> 01:13:13.720 position:56%
One of these blocks would take about
five hours to painstakingly melt

01:13:13.720 --> 01:13:21.070
with -- with a special tool and
then to lift clear of the surface.

01:13:21.070 --> 01:13:25.140
And so working closer with our
fleet diving units of Halifax

01:13:25.140 --> 01:13:30.620
and elsewhere in Pacific Region, we
conducted 80 dives over the course

01:13:30.620 --> 01:13:34.330
of five days and got to know the
wreck site a little bit better.

01:13:34.330 --> 01:13:37.440
I should mention this is
called Operation Inuvialuit,

01:13:37.440 --> 01:13:40.460
who was supported by
the United States in --

01:13:40.460 --> 01:13:44.460
in one respect, that
the camp was demobilized

01:13:44.460 --> 01:13:47.080
by two ski equipped C130 Hercules

01:13:47.080 --> 01:13:48.820
from the New York International
Guard.

01:13:48.820 --> 01:13:52.460
And so, these poor guys built
a runway on the ice for weeks,

01:13:52.460 --> 01:13:54.310
just plowing snow for weeks on end.

01:13:54.310 --> 01:13:58.160 position:56%
And finally, they were able to land
these gigantic Hercules planes to --

01:13:58.160 --> 01:14:02.650
to load all the camp in, which
made things much easier at the end.

01:14:02.650 --> 01:14:06.630 position:56%
So after the April dives, we
started preparing again for a return

01:14:06.630 --> 01:14:09.100
to the site this last
August and September,

01:14:09.100 --> 01:14:11.680
a year after the wreck discovery.

01:14:11.680 --> 01:14:15.190 position:56%
And enjoying some of the best
weather conditions we have ever seen

01:14:15.190 --> 01:14:16.920
working in the Arctic.

01:14:16.920 --> 01:14:22.970
Our team made in excess of 150
dives, clearing the overgrowth

01:14:22.970 --> 01:14:26.540
of kelp, which concealed a
lot of the ship's structures.

01:14:26.540 --> 01:14:30.380
And here you can see just
the remarkable water clarity

01:14:30.380 --> 01:14:32.220 position:56%
that they were enjoying at the time.

01:14:32.220 --> 01:14:35.310
This is like diving the Caribbean
in terms of how far you can see.

01:14:35.310 --> 01:14:37.840
So this is a view of the
port side of the Erebus

01:14:37.840 --> 01:14:39.460
with the exposed upper
deck beams where the --

01:14:39.460 --> 01:14:40.810
the deck planking has peeled away.

01:14:40.810 --> 01:14:44.720
And looking up at the
bow and you can get a --

01:14:44.720 --> 01:14:46.350
get a sense of how close
is just the surface,

01:14:46.350 --> 01:14:50.190 position:56%
the wreck being only 11 meters deep,

01:14:50.190 --> 01:14:53.750
the top being six meters below
the -- below the surface.

01:14:54.780 --> 01:14:59.720 position:56%
And along the port side, this again,
after all the kelp has been removed,

01:14:59.720 --> 01:15:03.420
you -- you really get a sense of
how well preserved the ship is,

01:15:03.420 --> 01:15:08.390
the ice channels on either
side of the hull, typical of --

01:15:08.390 --> 01:15:12.350
of Royal Navy ships
of Arctic exploration.

01:15:12.350 --> 01:15:15.870
And subtle details we can
finally see with the kelp removed,

01:15:15.870 --> 01:15:17.170
including the draft marks.

01:15:17.170 --> 01:15:20.310
Here you see this copper
cutout roman numerals,

01:15:20.310 --> 01:15:23.490
showing 20 feet this
height above the keel.

01:15:23.490 --> 01:15:28.150
And what's neat is that they're
half obscured by this iron plating.

01:15:28.150 --> 01:15:32.080
Like Investigator, Erebus
and Terror were both fitted

01:15:32.080 --> 01:15:35.650
with a five-sixteenths layer of
-- of plating of the bow to --

01:15:35.650 --> 01:15:38.650
to help protect the bows
from -- from ice damage.

01:15:38.650 --> 01:15:45.800 position:56%
But it's really the -- the artifacts
that tell an evocative story.

01:15:45.800 --> 01:15:48.190
Only after they were cleaned
in the lab, could you make much

01:15:48.190 --> 01:15:52.110
out of these two buttons
recovered from the lower deck,

01:15:52.110 --> 01:15:54.010
from actually inside
the ship and it --

01:15:54.010 --> 01:15:56.370
it is hard to see unless
you're holding it in your hand,

01:15:56.370 --> 01:16:01.020
but both show a fouled anchor
over the crown over top of it,

01:16:01.020 --> 01:16:02.850
symbol of the Royal Navy.

01:16:02.850 --> 01:16:06.600
And the lettering which took us a
while to make out, Royal Marines.

01:16:06.600 --> 01:16:10.350 position:56%
So both these buttons would
apparently derive from one of the --

01:16:10.350 --> 01:16:12.320
the jackets or tunics
from one of the --

01:16:12.320 --> 01:16:14.770
could be any from either ship,

01:16:14.770 --> 01:16:18.030
so one of the 13 Royal Marines
that entered the Arctic.

01:16:18.030 --> 01:16:22.980
And also really delicate
artifacts which tell us something

01:16:22.980 --> 01:16:26.680
about life onboard the ship
would only scratch the surface,

01:16:26.680 --> 01:16:28.580
but this is a patented
medicine bottle

01:16:28.580 --> 01:16:33.650
and it's embossed the name Samuel
Oxley and the other side, London.

01:16:33.650 --> 01:16:35.970
And Mr. Oxley was a royal chemist

01:16:35.970 --> 01:16:38.960
who at this time had
patented concentrated essence

01:16:38.960 --> 01:16:42.690 position:56%
of Jamaican ginger, which apparently
could cure just about anything,

01:16:42.690 --> 01:16:46.250 position:56%
including arthritis and seasickness,
which makes sense given the ginger.

01:16:46.250 --> 01:16:52.940
But also is a cure for
hypochondria ironically enough.

01:16:52.940 --> 01:16:56.470
And then the artifacts
just lying in plain view,

01:16:56.470 --> 01:16:59.670
here you see from [inaudible]
ceramic plates.

01:16:59.670 --> 01:17:03.470
Over here is a -- either a pewter

01:17:03.470 --> 01:17:07.230
or even perhaps a silver
plate, serving platter.

01:17:07.230 --> 01:17:10.410
And this is the circular
deck illuminator,

01:17:10.410 --> 01:17:15.000
one in which has fallen
down into the ship.

01:17:15.000 --> 01:17:18.090
After cleaning some
of the -- the poor --

01:17:18.090 --> 01:17:21.550
some of the ceramics
is really quite vivid.

01:17:21.550 --> 01:17:26.260 position:56%
And actually it preserves the -- the
stamps on the back and even the --

01:17:26.260 --> 01:17:31.780
the type, which is a Whampoa
pattern, which a lot of --

01:17:31.780 --> 01:17:35.320
of officers serving
in the -- in the --

01:17:35.320 --> 01:17:37.790
in the orient of would
return back to England

01:17:37.790 --> 01:17:39.810 position:56%
with their own personal collections.

01:17:39.810 --> 01:17:45.460
And this is where -- make reference
to when the ship was last seen,

01:17:45.460 --> 01:17:50.390
really before -- before we
stumbled upon it in 2014.

01:17:50.390 --> 01:17:54.140
And the Inuit's specifically
mention going onboard this ship,

01:17:54.140 --> 01:17:59.110
that they saw four sets
of footsteps trialing off

01:17:59.110 --> 01:18:03.970
to Adelaide Peninsula nearby,
perhaps the final survivors.

01:18:03.970 --> 01:18:08.820
That finally after the ship was
deserted, we think it would seem

01:18:08.820 --> 01:18:12.620
for a second time [inaudible]
that they went onboard

01:18:12.620 --> 01:18:14.260
and found everything
in complete order --

01:18:14.260 --> 01:18:18.880
the China plates that we see
there, spoons and knives and forks,

01:18:18.880 --> 01:18:22.620
likely which if they saw them, they
probably would have taken them,

01:18:22.620 --> 01:18:25.160
being quite useful
to modify the tools.

01:18:25.160 --> 01:18:28.750
And this rather interesting
artifact,

01:18:28.750 --> 01:18:31.060
this is a turned wooden table leg,

01:18:31.060 --> 01:18:34.460
it's mahogany with a detach
-- attached stretcher.

01:18:34.460 --> 01:18:39.090
And clearly, a table,
of -- but we --

01:18:39.090 --> 01:18:40.630
we suspected it might
in fact be this table.

01:18:40.630 --> 01:18:44.510 position:56%
This is an illustration from -- of
the Illustrated London News of 1845,

01:18:44.510 --> 01:18:46.120
during the month of departure.

01:18:46.120 --> 01:18:47.480
And actually, purports

01:18:47.480 --> 01:18:51.290
to show Franklin's own
cabin and this table here.

01:18:51.290 --> 01:18:55.880
And actually the -- the sonar
imagery shows that a big bite

01:18:55.880 --> 01:18:59.670
of the stern, the great cabin was
bitten away by the ice and a lot

01:18:59.670 --> 01:19:02.580
of these materials now have been
deposited straight to the seafloor.

01:19:02.580 --> 01:19:07.460
So, it's quite possibly
what we see right there.

01:19:07.460 --> 01:19:10.160
So this is the area in the --

01:19:10.160 --> 01:19:14.550
in the lower deck where we are
encountering a lot of these plates

01:19:14.550 --> 01:19:18.200
and -- and other scientific
instruments

01:19:18.200 --> 01:19:20.550 position:56%
and some other things I'll show you.

01:19:20.550 --> 01:19:24.210
But this is the area where the
common sailors would sling --

01:19:24.210 --> 01:19:26.880
sling their hammocks
and take their meals.

01:19:26.880 --> 01:19:29.830
In fact, if you look up at the
-- the upper deck beams overhead,

01:19:29.830 --> 01:19:32.600
you can see the hammock tags with
the numbers on them showing you

01:19:32.600 --> 01:19:35.970
where your particular
allotted space is.

01:19:35.970 --> 01:19:37.450
This is incredible detail.

01:19:37.450 --> 01:19:40.950
Again on the lower
deck inside the ship,

01:19:40.950 --> 01:19:44.740
this is a large chest
apparently some

01:19:44.740 --> 01:19:47.500
of the contents preserved inside.

01:19:47.500 --> 01:19:50.230
This we believe would have doubled
as the seats that they used for --

01:19:50.230 --> 01:19:53.560
at the mess tables as
the ship's plans show.

01:19:53.560 --> 01:20:00.540
This very delicate thing here
is -- you can see it here.

01:20:00.540 --> 01:20:06.630
This is a sword hilt or the
handle of a -- of a naval cutlass,

01:20:06.630 --> 01:20:09.400
which still preserves the --
all these subtle details, the --

01:20:09.400 --> 01:20:14.820
the sharkskin grip, the lion head
-- the [inaudible] and the --

01:20:14.820 --> 01:20:19.070
even the gold wire braid that kind
of holds the -- the grip together.

01:20:19.070 --> 01:20:23.400
Very, very ornate and really
interesting to us archaeologically,

01:20:23.400 --> 01:20:26.460
but quite possibly of no
interest whatsoever to the Inuit

01:20:26.460 --> 01:20:30.100
who quite possibly snapped off the
-- the steel blade and discarded,

01:20:30.100 --> 01:20:34.920
you know, this piece of, you know,
useless junk, as they would see it.

01:20:34.920 --> 01:20:38.210
So as we go ahead with
the archeological study

01:20:38.210 --> 01:20:40.440
of the wreck of the Erebus.

01:20:40.440 --> 01:20:44.270
We now go through -- we now enter
in to a very interesting stage

01:20:44.270 --> 01:20:47.420
where this is showing how
we've divided the area

01:20:47.420 --> 01:20:49.990
into [inaudible] areas
in order to contextualize

01:20:49.990 --> 01:20:53.750
where artifacts come from, to help
us identify associations with --

01:20:53.750 --> 01:20:58.960
with other finds to learn
more about the ship.

01:20:58.960 --> 01:21:03.000
And it's where we'll be in --

01:21:03.000 --> 01:21:04.370
in a position to answer some

01:21:04.370 --> 01:21:06.250
of these more interesting
archaeological questions.

01:21:06.250 --> 01:21:10.870
We believe that the ship was likely
re-manned, as the Inuit's suggest.

01:21:10.870 --> 01:21:14.300
We hope to go and identify
and show how it sank.

01:21:14.300 --> 01:21:17.860
We note that there's a [inaudible]
nearby with some materials lost

01:21:17.860 --> 01:21:21.080
or -- or deposited nearby
which possibly means

01:21:21.080 --> 01:21:23.650
that they may have escaped
the clutches of the ice only

01:21:23.650 --> 01:21:25.840
to run aground and
have the ship sink.

01:21:25.840 --> 01:21:29.070
Perhaps they didn't have enough
manpower at this point to --

01:21:29.070 --> 01:21:32.540
to adequate man the ship's pumps
and/or to lighten to get it off.

01:21:32.540 --> 01:21:35.050
Hopefully we'll find out.

01:21:35.050 --> 01:21:36.350
In the case of --

01:21:36.350 --> 01:21:43.310
of the Investigator where
you can start seeing the --

01:21:43.310 --> 01:21:48.550
the tensions simmering as
men who are on short rations

01:21:48.550 --> 01:21:52.120
and the officers are starting
to second guess, perhaps the --

01:21:52.120 --> 01:21:55.860
the command decisions
or at least privately.

01:21:55.860 --> 01:21:58.480
Did the discipline of the
Franklin Expedition breakdown?

01:21:58.480 --> 01:22:01.820
If the men came back to the
ship, was it because the --

01:22:01.820 --> 01:22:06.690
the party had fractured or was
it all survivors at that point

01:22:06.690 --> 01:22:07.990
who returned to the ship?

01:22:07.990 --> 01:22:09.290
We don't know.

01:22:09.290 --> 01:22:12.520
Is -- anthropologically, is there
evidence of the Inuit going onboard

01:22:12.520 --> 01:22:15.570 position:56%
and harvesting useful raw
materials, sifting through materials

01:22:15.570 --> 01:22:19.490
on the lower deck, collecting the
knives and discarding the ship's,

01:22:19.490 --> 01:22:24.100
you know, portraits and
paintings and that sort of thing?

01:22:24.100 --> 01:22:28.380
We have to be able to test some
of the prevailing hypothesis

01:22:28.380 --> 01:22:31.650
about what happened to
the Franklin Expedition,

01:22:31.650 --> 01:22:35.180
Inuit reports seeing
unopened tins of -- of meat.

01:22:35.180 --> 01:22:38.760
Maybe we'll find them, maybe
we'll be able to test the quality.

01:22:38.760 --> 01:22:43.110
The theory of lead poisoning being
a longstanding contributing factor,

01:22:43.110 --> 01:22:45.820
as -- as has been hypothesized.

01:22:45.820 --> 01:22:48.760
So we'll beable to test
some of these views.

01:22:48.760 --> 01:22:52.450
And ultimately, archaeologically
we want to figure out what happened

01:22:52.450 --> 01:22:53.890
in the final stages of
the Franklin Expedition

01:22:53.890 --> 01:22:57.280
and what really caused
the expedition to fail.

01:22:57.280 --> 01:23:00.470
Although I -- I think that's
really [inaudible] question

01:23:00.470 --> 01:23:05.390
because I think the Franklin
Expedition failed on May 1845,

01:23:05.390 --> 01:23:07.400
when they received their
orders from the Admiralty.

01:23:07.400 --> 01:23:10.670
And really that's when
they were directed into one

01:23:10.670 --> 01:23:13.190
of the worst ice choke points
in the Canadian Arctic.

01:23:13.190 --> 01:23:16.300
A place situated along the west
coast of King William Island

01:23:16.300 --> 01:23:17.940
where the Inuit would
almost never travel

01:23:17.940 --> 01:23:20.910
because there's nothing
to subsist on.

01:23:20.910 --> 01:23:22.290
What we can tell from the --

01:23:22.290 --> 01:23:26.350
the [inaudible] note left on
King William Island recovered

01:23:26.350 --> 01:23:29.380
by the McClintock party, as
Franklin apparently ordered his --

01:23:29.380 --> 01:23:31.770
followed his orders to the letter.

01:23:31.770 --> 01:23:36.080
He was proceeding after trying
to identify a north Polar Sea,

01:23:36.080 --> 01:23:39.530
which doesn't exist, but proceeding
southwest to the surveyed part

01:23:39.530 --> 01:23:41.960
of the North American mainland.

01:23:41.960 --> 01:23:44.280
I'm not sure that -- that Franklin

01:23:44.280 --> 01:23:46.840
and his men really
ever stood a chance,

01:23:46.840 --> 01:23:49.450
no matter what they would have
done, which as most brings us

01:23:49.450 --> 01:23:51.860 position:56%
to this interesting question of the
discovery of the North-West Passage,

01:23:51.860 --> 01:23:55.640
which -- which Glenn
was speaking to.

01:23:55.640 --> 01:24:00.790 position:56%
And I can't help but think of the --
the Franklin Monument that is placed

01:24:00.790 --> 01:24:06.950 position:56%
in Waterloo Place in London, where
really at the assistance of his wife

01:24:06.950 --> 01:24:11.000
or widow, Lady Jane Franklin,
the credit was given to Franklin

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:13.060
and his men for forging
the last link

01:24:13.060 --> 01:24:15.130
of the North-West Passage
with their lives.

01:24:15.130 --> 01:24:17.280
This years after the Investigator

01:24:17.280 --> 01:24:20.930
and the crew had been awarded
the 10,000 pound Admiralty prize

01:24:20.930 --> 01:24:23.080
for accomplishing that feat.

01:24:23.080 --> 01:24:24.650
Of course, they live
to tell the tale

01:24:24.650 --> 01:24:27.520
and that really is the
fundamental difference.

01:24:27.520 --> 01:24:31.090
Significantly whoever --
finding Erebus where it lies,

01:24:31.090 --> 01:24:32.850
and given the possibility
that we might be able

01:24:32.850 --> 01:24:34.850
to test archaeologically
that it had been re-manned.

01:24:34.850 --> 01:24:37.420
There's every possibility that the
men onboard that ship new exactly

01:24:37.420 --> 01:24:40.290
where they were and in fact,
knew that they had affected

01:24:40.290 --> 01:24:45.490
that last link and had
linked up with the --

01:24:45.490 --> 01:24:48.130
the shoreline survey by
Simpson [inaudible] in 1839.

01:24:48.130 --> 01:24:51.520
It was probably a small
consolation for the fate

01:24:51.520 --> 01:24:52.910 position:56%
that would surely befall on whoever.

01:24:52.910 --> 01:24:55.290
I'll leave it at that and in hopes

01:24:55.290 --> 01:24:57.650 position:56%
that we might have some
interesting questions and discussion

01:24:57.650 --> 01:24:59.070
with whatever time remains.

01:24:59.070 --> 01:25:00.840
And I thank you very
much for your interest.

01:25:00.840 --> 01:25:02.640
Cheers.

01:25:02.640 --> 01:25:07.040
[ Applause ]

