01:25:53.280 --> 01:25:54.640
in Canada.

01:25:54.640 --> 01:26:00.180 position:56%
And really together, we need to have
both to flush out all the details

01:26:00.180 --> 01:26:05.760
of what happened to the
-- to the Franklin party.

01:26:05.760 --> 01:26:09.240
Also, first to protect and preserve
that second wreck site for --

01:26:09.240 --> 01:26:11.020 position:56%
for posterity, for the benefit of --

01:26:11.020 --> 01:26:14.210
of Canadians and people who
are interested worldwide.

01:26:14.210 --> 01:26:16.640
We have to identify the
wreck site and figure

01:26:16.640 --> 01:26:17.940
out what sort of condition it's in.

01:26:17.940 --> 01:26:22.860
So yes, we will be continuing that
effort for the foreseeable future.

01:26:25.110 --> 01:26:30.810
&gt;&gt; Two things on the demise
that came to my detection.

01:26:30.810 --> 01:26:34.610
Could Franklin had backed
out when he hit that ice

01:26:34.610 --> 01:26:36.650
that you and I were discussing?

01:26:36.650 --> 01:26:39.480
I had an impression that he had a
shot at getting out [inaudible].

01:26:39.480 --> 01:26:45.620
And the second thing, the food
poisoning, hadn't it already set

01:26:45.620 --> 01:26:50.760
into the extent that without
some alternate source of food,

01:26:50.760 --> 01:26:53.700
they were going to die anyway?

01:26:53.700 --> 01:26:55.130
&gt;&gt; Ryan Harris: Yes,
very good questions.

01:26:55.130 --> 01:26:58.820
I wish I could say demise with
that sort of a dramatic emphasis

01:26:58.820 --> 01:27:02.870
that you were capable
of, and that's great.

01:27:02.870 --> 01:27:08.040
You has asked when -- when the
ships became beset in Larson Sound,

01:27:08.040 --> 01:27:12.720
so north of King William Island
in 1846, was that avoidable?

01:27:12.720 --> 01:27:16.680
Ultimately, was -- was
that an error in judgment?

01:27:16.680 --> 01:27:19.050
Well, we don't necessarily know,
I mean, that's sort of difficult

01:27:19.050 --> 01:27:20.350
to reconstruct those moments,

01:27:20.350 --> 01:27:23.720
but what we certainly can say
having surveyed in those waters

01:27:23.720 --> 01:27:28.910
for several years now, that the
ice conditions can change very,

01:27:28.910 --> 01:27:30.210
very quickly.

01:27:30.210 --> 01:27:33.430
Particularly late in the
season, come late September,

01:27:33.430 --> 01:27:37.290
there's an almost inexhaustible
supply of ice constantly coming

01:27:37.290 --> 01:27:39.450
down McClintock Channel
to the northwest.

01:27:39.450 --> 01:27:44.250 position:56%
And that if the wind -- the wind had
been blowing easterly and then all

01:27:44.250 --> 01:27:47.260
of a sudden swung to the northwest,
very quickly there would be a wall

01:27:47.260 --> 01:27:50.650
of ice right on top of them.

01:27:50.650 --> 01:27:55.730
You can also experience
flash freezes where a change

01:27:55.730 --> 01:27:58.990
in wind direction will bring
remarkably colder temperatures

01:27:58.990 --> 01:28:03.200
and you can have dramatic
freezing right away.

01:28:03.200 --> 01:28:04.890
A lot of this information
comes to us

01:28:04.890 --> 01:28:08.480
from a historical ice climatology
study that was conducted for us

01:28:08.480 --> 01:28:12.120
by Tom Zagonoff -- Zagon of
our Canadian Ice Service,

01:28:12.120 --> 01:28:15.500 position:56%
trying to reconstruct the prevailing
patterns of ice formation drift

01:28:15.500 --> 01:28:18.950
and breakup in Victoria Strait to
help us try to narrow our search,

01:28:18.950 --> 01:28:21.780
because otherwise we're left
with a considerable area.

01:28:21.780 --> 01:28:25.350
Also a -- yeah, it's -- it's --

01:28:25.350 --> 01:28:30.340
it's [inaudible] safe if they
would have had anywhere else to go,

01:28:30.340 --> 01:28:32.030
they couldn't necessarily
have just doubled back

